article.headline: Lewis scores 27 in return
article.linkText: Lewis' return blasts Sonics past Rockets
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The best therapy for Rashard Lewis was a return to the court. It was just what his teammates needed, too. Lewis scored 27 points and rookie Luke Ridnour had eight of his 11 points in the fourth quarter for the Seattle SuperSonics, who beat the Houston Rockets 95-88 Saturday night. Lewis, who shot 9-of-18 from the floor, missed Friday night's loss at Utah after his brother's death. "I just feel the best way for me (to cope) is to be on out the court and be around my teammates, talking about basketball 24-7," Lewis said. "I think the best thing for me is to continue playing basketball, to keep my mind on basketball." Lewis was so eager to focus on his game that he considered rejoining the Sonics in Salt Lake City. "I was worried about the team. We've been struggling and losing games," he said. "It was hard for me to leave but I had to because it was a close family member. I didn't want to miss both games. I tried to get back as quickly as possible." Antonio Daniels made his first start of the season, scoring 13 points, while Ronald Murray came off the bench for 12 and Brent Barry added 10. The Sonics had lost three of four at home. "From the moment the horn started until it sounded at the end, we fought," Daniels said. "They went on a nice little run. We still fought. We stayed together on both ends of the floor. We needed a game like this." Steve Francis led the Rockets with 28 points, but he scored only four in the fourth quarter -- all from the foul line. Ridnour had something to do with that, as the rookie point guard guarded Francis for much of the final period. The Rockets shot 8-for-33 in the second half. They hit 9-of-17 from the foul line in the fourth quarter. "We missed a lot of shots down the stretch, a lot of layups," Francis said. "I thought we were intense, but they somehow got some loose balls and some easy buckets that really hurt us." Yao Ming scored 19 points with nine rebounds, but Seattle's strategy was to keep throwing bodies at him. Jerome James fouled out, but Calvin Booth and Vitaly Potapenko did their part to slow him. "I was worn out. I was beaten up," Yao said through a translator. Ridnour had a spectacular fourth quarter, going 3-for-5 from the floor and, when he wasn't shooting, finding open teammates. He either scored or assisted on five of the first six Sonics baskets in the period. "I thought Ridnour did a good job running pick-and-rolls," Houston coach Jeff Van Gundy said. The rookie also spent much of the period defending Francis, who hit four free throws for his only points of the final period and missed a 3-pointer with 29.5 seconds to go with Houston trailing 91-87. Ridnour hit two baskets, one a 3-pointer, and Murray added another jumper as the Sonics built an 86-77 lead with 5:06 remaining. "Luke really kept the lead for us," Lewis said. "He hit a few big jump shots for us when we really stretched the lead." Seattle erased a 56-52 halftime deficit, using a 16-8 run over the last 8:40 of the third period to make it a game. They rallied with steady defense, holding the Rockets to one field goal for a 14-minute stretch over the third and fourth quarters, and good ball movement to create open shots.

Game notes
Sonics coach Nate McMillan benched Murray for the first time this season, starting Daniels. James also got his first start while Booth came off the bench. ... The Rockets fell to 7-2 when leading at halftime. ... Houston wrapped up a 1-4 road trip with only one win, beating the Los Angeles Clippers.
